{{short description|an advanced ballet class}} The '''class of perfection''' ({{lang-fr|classe de perfectionnement}}) is an advanced [[ballet]] class for the highest ranking [[ballerina]]s in a ballet company. In Russia, the traditional class of perfection has been replaced by the unified company class,<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1080/01472526.2012.720960| issn = 0147-2526| volume = 35| issue = 3| pages = 408–413| last = Rizzo| first = Laura Katz| title = Vaganova's Vision and the Development of Neoclassical Russian Ballet Technique| journal = Dance Chronicle| accessdate = 2018-04-29| date = 2012-09-01| url = https://doi.org/10.1080/01472526.2012.720960}}</ref> but the term may still be used informally for the special classes taken by only the highest ranking dancers in a company.<ref name=greskovic>{{Cite book| publisher = Hal Leonard Corporation| isbn = 978-0-87910-325-5| last = Greskovic| first = Robert| title = Ballet 101: A Complete Guide to Learning and Loving the Ballet| date = 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media | people= Ekaterina Krysanova (prima ballerina) | date=July 30, 2013 | title=Dance class with the Bolshoi ballet | location=London | publisher=The Telegraph |archive-url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DhqzAVMHKZk}}</ref>
==Early history== The class of perfection at the [[Imperial Choreographic School]] was taught by [[Christian Johansson]], who had himself been a pupil of Danish balletmaster [[August Bournonville]]. After Johansson, the responsibility of teaching the class passed to his former student [[Nikolai Legat]]. Many of [[Russian ballet]]s legendary dancers were once pupils of Legat's class of perfection including [[Njinsky]], [[Mikhail Fokine]] and the most important ballerinas of the time. Ballet mistress [[Agrippina Vaganova]] had also been one of Legat's class of perfection students.<ref name=newman>{{Cite book| publisher = Hal Leonard Corporation| isbn = 978-0-87910-995-0| last = Newman| first = Barbara| title = Grace Under Pressure: Passing Dance Through Time| date = 2003}}</ref>
